{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"08ff7bfd-dee4-4ec4-9037-b17118a6be2f","content":"## What happened\n\nApple removed DSA support from its native **Security.framework** (deprecated since macOS 10.15, fully removed in later releases). On macOS, .NET delegates cryptographic operations to this native framework. Starting in .NET 11, the runtime no longer papers over the missing platform support, so **`DSA.Create()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** on macOS.\n\nWindows and Linux are unaffected — Windows uses CNG (which still supports DSA) and Linux uses OpenSSL.\n\n## How to fix it\n\nSince you only need to **verify** legacy signatures (not generate new ones), you have two practical options:\n\n### Option 1 — Use BouncyCastle (recommended, fully managed)\n\n```bash\ndotnet add package BouncyCastle.Cryptography\n```\n\n```csharp\nusing Org.BouncyCastle.Crypto.Parameters;\nusing Org.BouncyCastle.Security;\n\nbool VerifyDsaSignature(byte[] message, byte[] signature, DsaPublicKeyParameters publicKey)\n{\n    var signer = SignerUtilities.GetSigner(\"SHA256withDSA\");\n    signer.Init(forSigning: false, publicKey);\n    signer.BlockUpdate(message, 0, message.Length);\n    return signer.VerifySignature(signature);\n}\n```\n\nThis is pure managed code — no platform dependencies at all.\n\n### Option 2 — Use `DSAOpenSsl` explicitly on macOS\n\nInstall OpenSSL on macOS (`brew install openssl`) and use the OpenSSL-specific class:\n\n```csharp\nusing System.Security.Cryptography;\n\nDSA CreateDsa()\n{\n    if (OperatingSystem.IsMacOS())\n        return new DSAOpenSsl();   // requires OpenSSL on PATH / DYLD_LIBRARY_PATH\n    return DSA.Create();           // CNG on Windows, OpenSSL on Linux\n}\n```\n\nThis adds a deployment dependency on Homebrew OpenSSL for macOS machines.\n\n## Recommendation\n\nGo with **BouncyCastle**. It's a managed implementation with no native dependency, so it works identically on all three platforms. Since DSA is legacy, it also positions you to eventually migrate signature verification to RSA or ECDSA without another platform-coupling headache.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"643ea634-36eb-4618-be38-e2a44e6360f9","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET compatibility issue with DSA (Digital Signature Algorithm) on macOS after upgrading from .NET 10 to .NET 11. Let me reason about this from my knowledge of .NET's evolution and Apple's platform changes.\n\nThis is a known breaking change in .NET. Let me explain what happened:\n\nApple deprecated and then removed support for DSA (Digital Signature Algorithm) from their cryptographic frameworks (CommonCrypto/Security.framework). Starting with macOS, Apple's platform no longer supports DSA operations.\n\nIn .NET, the `DSA.Create()` method on macOS relied on Apple's native cryptographic libraries. When Apple removed DSA support, .NET followed suit. Specifically, .NET removed the DSA implementation on macOS because the underlying platform no longer supports it.\n\n\nThe breaking change means `DSA.Create()` now throws a `PlatformNotSupportedException` on macOS in newer .NET versions. Apple deprecated DSA support back in macOS 10.15 and iOS 13, and .NET eventually aligned with that platform limitation.\n\nGiven the timeline the user mentioned—.NET 10 (released November 2025) working fine but .NET 11 (currently in preview as of May 2026) breaking—I'm wondering if .NET 10 still had some managed or OpenSSL-based fallback for DSA on macOS that was removed in .NET 11. Since .NET's macOS runtime relies on Apple's Security.framework for cryptographic operations, and Apple completely removed DSA from their APIs in macOS 12.0, the runtime eventually had to drop support entirely.\n\nThe practical solution here is to either use an OpenSSL binding through a NuGet package, implement P/Invoke to call OpenSSL directly, or ship OpenSSL alongside the application to handle DSA operations outside of the native framework. I should focus on giving a straightforward answer since the user is asking a diagnostic question about a known platform limitation, not requesting code changes or implementation details.","outputTokens":1582,"requestId":"984E:1FBC5F:297948:33E353:69F555F8"},"id":"07ef61ab-f1cd-4174-bea0-22acf64de444","timestamp":"2026-05-02T01:40:40.653Z","parentId":"57bbe127-9726-4938-9e60-a20590271c44"}
